        <h3 data-uuid="961d5b89e8ca4b15a7237d7256b9c14f">Cold War Crises</h3>
        <p data-uuid="b0ae4a4b70204b3fa6a11b88809fe184">President Eisenhower modified Truman’s
            policy of containment. He and Secretary of State John Foster Dulles supported <dfn title="brinkmanship">brinkmanship</dfn>—a
            willingness to go to the brink of war to oppose communism. “The ability to get
            to the verge [edge] without getting into war is the necessary art,” Dulles explained.
            The president and Dulles also threatened the Soviet Union with “massive
            retaliation” against Soviet advances.</p>
        <p data-uuid="1f09c5491eb04a3094ab7eadfa3622d3">As part of his effort, Eisenhower used
            covert, or secret, operations around the world. In 1953, for example, the
            Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) helped overthrow the premier of Iran.
            American officials had feared he was a Communist. In 1954 the CIA helped
            organize the removal of the Guatemalan president for similar reasons.</p>
        <section class="extension" data-uuid="a2473708551e4a9fa3ebeed036aa35f8">
            <object type="text/html" data="../../assets/widgets/extension/index.html" class="widget" width="900" data-uuid="528b09d1854941c8a5633e4250973c5d">
                <param name="configFile" value="../../widget_data/config/528b09d1854941c8a5633e4250973c5d.json" />
