        <p data-uuid="3568d22cf258465d8de9ea3fbeb00127">In 1956 a crisis in
            Egypt seemed to push the world to the brink of a third world war. Egyptian
            leader Gamal Abdel Nasser nationalized the Suez Canal, a vital waterway
            connecting the Mediterranean and Red seas, in an attempt to collect tolls from
            the canal to finance a major dam project. Britain and France, which relied on
            the canal for trade, allied with Israel, a longtime enemy of Egypt, and invaded
            the area around the canal. The Soviet Union, an ally of Egypt, threatened to
            crush the &#173;invaders. This would force the United States to defend its allies.
            Finally, the Americans and the Soviet Union agreed to condemn the invasion, and
            the Suez crisis ended. After the brief moment of cooperation, the Cold War
            continued.<br />
        </p>
